segments.text: And there weren't any problems.
I think if you ask people for advice and take it as good, you'll be all right.
But if you just ignore them and say, we're going to do it this way, nobody appreciates that.
Well, that was the reason that we made the growth we did in horticulture, was because I asked people's advice.
They gave me three choices.
And I took their advice, if I could fit it in any way.
without disturbing them.
That was all there was to it.
Let me be sure of that.
In the teaching faculty, who were the really outstanding people in the program?
Bloodworth, I mean, isn't that awful?
Homer Blackhurst, once the board came back and was there for 40 years,
He was very stable, and I depended on him a lot.
I knew I couldn't depend on DeWorth, because DeWorth, everything I did, it was wrong with DeWorth.
And such a letting all the girls in.
You'll regret that the longest day you live.
Describe Blackhurst's specialties.
Peas, cow peas, I forgot what, I think it was cow peas.
He did research on a certain kind of peas.
and did it for years.
But he taught freshman horticulture, which is beginning horticulture, many, many years.
In fact, he saved Harvard during the war, or they wouldn't have had anybody.
And when I wrote the citation up for our distinguished professor of the Harvard students,
I put on there that he had saved the department during the war.
And had it not been for Blackhurst hanging around and doing this, we wouldn't have had anybody to work with.
But I was so glad to get him that distinguished award.
I told the kids how to write it up, everything.
And I got it.
I was on the way to St. Louis to a meeting.
No, I'm on the way to a big program in Kansas City.
And I stopped just outside of Kansas City, and I called up Blackhurst person to person.
I said, would you mind telling me what time it is?
And he said, well, I got a hold of the secretary.
She told me all about it, too.
But he was very deserving of it.
Any guy that stays out of the job 40 years, regardless of what he's doing, deserves to be recognized.
And I felt so, even though I had people that didn't agree with me.
They don't always have to agree with me.
If I'm calling shots, I'm going to call them like I think they're right.
And I thought that Blackhurst needed it.
And you know the interesting thing about Blackhurst?
He died in his sleep Christmas Eve.
She died talking on the phone a week later.
talking to one of the daughters.
And before the diamond wanted to get there, she just toppled over.
But he came from West Virginia.
He was a character, but I enjoyed Homer and enjoyed working with him.
You could work with Homer any time.
You just never did.
He never did really pursue you.
The worst is it drove me crazy.
And last year, I was there, and he was still there.
Oh, my, I couldn't do anything wrong.
Right, every day, he'd tell me what I'd done wrong and what was going to happen and all that.
So I just said, well, that's your private privilege.
As you look back on those years, of what are you most proud of?
reorganizing horticulture, rebuilding horticulture.
I did that.
Well, that's the job I think I did the best job on academically, and I'm proudest of that.
And I didn't have any trouble with that.
It just took a little while to do it.
And, no, that's the thing I am, in academics, that's the thing I think I,
I pride myself more, or anything else, is rebuilding Harder Coater into a viable department.
And it was a good one, too.
But you take time.
You see, I went up to McCandless and asked for a special fund to re-equip the office.
And you had no one you were going to be.
So I got some match furniture.
And I went down and bought a little rug myself and put it in there, but it didn't work.
When he just disappeared, he took all that furniture with him across the track to one of those shacks over there.
Who's that?
The department here that they hired, Mr. Garlick.
I mean, he just disappeared one night.
I came in, and all the furniture was gone.
That had been bought on a special phone from McAnlis, the former department head.
And I felt he was staying in that office, but he didn't stay there.
You retired when?
I retired in, let me see.
You know, that had a pitfall in it.
I retired in 76, I believe.
As you look back, are there any people that you would want to thank that we haven't mentioned?
I can never thank Ms. Runner enough for what she did for me.
She let me take the president's home and use it as a lab, too.
In the class.
And this was the new president's home.
Yes.
And Jack Ridge was there for a while in that home.
And now let's see.
Well, I'll always be grateful to Blackhurst.
And Dr. Nightingale was a very good friend of mine.
And I admired him because, oh, he was treating something awful about Dorothy.
He would have a research project set up.
DeWorthy would come in and just throw it all out.
And how he put up with it, I do not know, but he did.
And then I hired Bill one time along to come and help me with the flowers on campus, because he was raising all this stuff up at Waco.
And DeWorthy came in one day and said, you sure you made a mistake hiring that old boy?
I said, well, prop?
You taught him all he knows.
You couldn't afford to take anything off that man, or he'd run you under his feet.
So I just made a point that I didn't argue with him.
I just said, well, that's your opinion.
But when he said I was making a mistake letting all the girls in, and I said, well, I'm not letting them in.
They're taxpayers' daughters.
That just made him furious with me.
But you have to
do what you think's right at the time.
Let's see.
Other people that you want to thank?
Well, Dick Potts and I, we never made horticulture without his help.
Because there were so many loopholes to fill with the students.
No one had ever given any counseling advising.
They didn't know what they were supposed to take or when they were supposed to take it.
And I could go down and work with Dick and he'd help me over the pumps.
Oh, and Nelda in the president's office.
Nelda Rowell then, now Nelda Green.
Yes.
Oh, she is a jewel.
And she helped me over many rough spots.
Give some examples.
Oh, I'd go in and just tell her I had that.
Well, I'll tell you one that really got me.
This is the outstanding one, I think.
You know, the court arms have walks, a big walk on.
Well, I know when they reported, they were very thin, no reinforcing in them.
And there were all kinds of big trucks coming in there, especially the vendors' trucks and the trash trucks.
So the first thing I did, I closed the thing to nothing but emergency vehicles.
A check sale came to see me, mad.
He says,
We're going to stop this.
We have to get in there.
I said, no, you don't.
You're making money off of us, and we have a right to tell you what you can do and what you can't do.
And he was a twice-meter man.
Oh, he said, I'll go see Roderick about this.
Before he got there, I put on the phone with Nelda.
I said, Nelda, let me talk to Mr. Roderick real quick.
I said, we have a man that insists on bringing those heavy trucks in there.
And he's making money off of us.
I think we have every right to tell him where he can park and how he can make the money.
He says, I'll do it too.
I'll wait for him.
And so we did more.
You know, you have to do what you think is right and stick by it.
And they had no minutes coming in there, breaking up those walks.
The kids had to walk on them.
Anyway, we got that done.
We also cleaned up the core area and hauled 59 truckloads of trash out of there and found 34 wall building plaques in the stuff.
Oh, there's a lot of things to do.
But I enjoyed my time.
All right.
I'm near the end of my questions.
I want to be sure to mention to you, if you have any memorabilia and papers or anything relating to A&M that you ever want to dispose of, please put them in the A&M archives.
They will preserve them and protect them.
You know, all of that got lost in the move that I've made, but at least I think it has.
I'm trying to think.
When they moved us
up here to assisted living.
My daughter and my son put all that stuff, they put a lot of it up here, all they could get up here.
But it's in an air-conditioned warehouse somewhere in Conroe.
Well, if there are any papers, because this would be like the treasure house of the materials relating to A&M, and nobody else will care for them as well as the archives would.
That's right.
Well, I'll ask my daughter.
I can't remember if I had a file on me.
I'm sure I did.
Well, if you did.
But I don't know what to do.
Whether it's students, faculty, student papers, faculty, it doesn't matter.
All right, then the next to last one.

Let's make believe that somebody walked up to you today and gave you a check for a million dollars, and there was only one condition to the gift, that you must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you decide what use would be made of it.
What would you want to help A&M to do?
Well, I'd want most of it to go back to scholarships.
I guess they got lots of scholarships, but they haven't worked my way through A&M pretty hard.
I'd want it to go to students.
Would you want them identified as to major or anything?
Would that matter?
Just students?
I've got a committee that does that.
All right.
All right, then my last question is, what are your feelings about A&M?
Great.
Couldn't be better.
I love A&M.
I always will love it.
And as I said, what's the Aggie spirit?
You can't tell what the Aggie spirit is.
It just grows on you, and it's the part of it that you absorb during life that you don't get any other way.
And I cherish all the years that I had there
both as a student and faculty and everything.
I have a few regrets that I couldn't get along with Paul Stevens.
I couldn't get a lot of my stuff done, because every time I turned, he was blocking it or blowing cigar smoke in my face and those kind of things I didn't like.
And I had the freedom to do things I wanted to do.
I'm trying to think who the assistant dean of agriculture was at the time, and he was thinking West Campus as an ag campus.
And we went down there to talk to Stevens about some possibilities of a building.
And he said, I don't want to go back in there and talk to that man any minute.
He don't quite understand me.
I told him I was going to make this an ag campus, and he said, he just told me that he didn't do campus planning, and he didn't go in and do it.
Just forget it.
And I said, that's right.
He's calling the shots.
All right, let's quit with that.
